Entropy rates from human DNA - results¶

First, the algorith written in Python3 was tested against a very long english text - the text was adjusted for words and spaces. The adjusted text has 6 115 909 letters.

Division of sequencies of the Homo Sapiens genome We divided the sequences of the Homo Sapiens genome into two parts: 1. sequencies of the Homo Sapiens genome, which vary only a little among people - sequencioes of coding genes. As a base we downloaded the file Homo_sapiens.GRCh38.cdna.all.fa.gz from ftp://ftp.ensembl.org/pub/release-99/fasta/homo_sapiens/cdna/ There are the sequencies of coding genes }i.e. the file of many shorter parts (not a continual long part). 2. sequencies of the Homo Sapiens genome, which vary among people. But not the whole sequencies, only small parts of them. We choose among-genes sequencies, which we downloaded from ftp://ftp.ensembl.org/pub/release-99/fasta/homo_sapiens/dna/ and filtered out the sequencies parts, which are in the file Homo_sapiens.GRCh38.99.gtf.gz from ftp://ftp.ensembl.org/pub/release-99/gtf/homo_sapiens/. This gtf file shows us, where the gene sequencies placed. So we filtered out the gene sequencies and worked onlz with the among-genes sequencies. DNA (Deoxyribonucleic acid) Deoxyribonucleic acid is a molecule which consists of two chains that form a double helix with genetic information of life organisms. The two DNA strands are called polynucleotides and are composed of monomeric units called nucleotides.Each nucleotide is composed of one of four nitrogen-containing nucleobases (cytosine [C], guanine [G], adenine [A] or thymine [T]). The nitrogenous bases of the two separate polynucleotide strands are bound together, according to base pairing rules (A with T and C with G), with hydrogen bonds to make double-stranded DNA. The nitrogenous bases are divided into two groups, pyrimidines (thymine and cytosine) and purines (adenine and guanine). A large part of DNA (in case of humas it is more than 98 %) is non-coding. Humans are eukaryotic organisms and store most of their DNA inside the cell nucleus as nuclear DNA. DNA of eukaryotic organism is organized into structures called chromosomes. In our survey, we took as the base samples contaning 1 000 000 and 10 000 000 of DNA letter (ATCG) of the human genome - chromosome 22.

def count_mod_and_stat(adjusted_file_in, part_of_letters):         #Markov
    d_stat=od()
    d_mod=od()
    
    f_in=open(adjusted_file_in,'r')
    rows_in = f_in.read()
          
    moving_window = deque(maxlen = part_of_letters)
    
    for j in rows_in:
            
        key=''.join(moving_window)
        moving_window.append(j)
##      print(part_of_letters,key)
        if len(key) == part_of_letters:
            if key not in d_mod:
                d_mod[key] = od()
                                  
            if j in d_mod[key]:
                d_mod[key][j] += 1                   
            else:
                d_mod[key][j] = 1                   
                
            if key in d_stat:
                d_stat[key] += 1
            else:                    
                d_stat[key] = 1
 
    f_in.close()
    return d_mod,d_stat

In [ ]:
def entropy_for_key(d_mod_part, d_stat_part):
	return -sum(v / d_stat_part * math.log2(v / d_stat_part) for v in d_mod_part.values())
In [ ]:
def entropy_rate(model, stats):
	return sum(stats[stat] * entropy_for_key(model[stat], stats[stat]) for stat in stats) / sum(stats.values())
